e Coming of the White Men [Julius Fouts] -- tOrigination of White Men [Julius Fouts] -- tWhites & Indians [Charles Elkhair] -- t7. Tales of Ordinary Life -- tIntroduction -- tA Child’s Life [Julius Fouts] -- tThe Three Clans [Julius Fouts] -- tThe Origin of Stories -- tAn Afterword in Three Parts -- tI. What Happened to the Storytellers? -- tII. Four Elders at the End of the Century -- tIII. Today -- tAppendix A: The Turtle’s Back (Iroquoian and Munsee Versions) -- tAppendix B: Dutch Arrival at Manhattan (John Heckewelder’s Version) -- tAppendix C: The Woman Who Wanted No One (as told to Truman Michelson) -- tAppendix D: Elected Leaders of the Delaware Tribe of Indians, ca. 1800–Present -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Lenape tribe, also known as the Delaware Nation, lived for centuries on the land that English colonists later called New Jersey. But once America gained its independence, they were forced to move further west: to Indiana, then Missouri, and finally to the territory that became Oklahoma. These reluctant migrants were not able to carry much from their ancestral homeland, but they managed to preserve the stories that had been passed down for generations. On the Turtle’s Back is the first collection of Lenape folklore, originally compiled by anthropologist M. R. Harrington over a century ago but never published until now. In it, the Delaware share their cherished tales about the world’s creation, epic heroes, and ordinary human foibles. It features stories told to Harrington by two Lenape couples, Julius and Minnie Fouts and Charles and Susan Elkhair, who sought to officially record their legends before their language and cultural traditions died out. More recent interviews with Lenape elders are also included, as their reflections on hearing these stories as children speak to the status of the tribe and its culture today. Together, they welcome you into their rich and wondrous imaginative world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDelaware IndiansvBiography. 0aDelaware IndiansxFolklore. 0aDelaware IndianszOklahomaxSocial life and customs. 0aDelaware Indians. 0aDelaware languagevTexts. 0aIndians of North AmericazOklahomaxFolklore. 0aIndians of North AmericazOklahomaxSocial life and customs. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh  alenape, delaware, native american, american indian, indigenous, new jersey, folklore, mythology, oral history, anthropology, culture, delaware nation, lenape nation.1 aMichael, Nicky Kay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197881918440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978819184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978819184/original  a978-3-11-079130-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles